05165nam a22008055i 9780801468865DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979723688  a97808014688657 a10.7591/97808014688652doi  a(DE-B1597)478711  a(OCoLC)857077253  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDK4727.N69bL43 2016 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a943.8622231 aLebow, Katherine A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnfinished Utopia :bNowa Huta, Stalinism, and Polish Society, 1949–56 /cKatherine A. Lebow. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b15 halftones, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Unplanned City -- t2. New Men -- t3. The Poor Worker Breaks His Legs -- t4. Women of Steel -- t5. The Enlightenment of Kasza -- t6. Spaces of Solidarity, 1956–89 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnfinished Utopia is a social and cultural history of Nowa Huta, dubbed Poland's "first socialist city" by Communist propaganda of the 1950s. Work began on the new town, located on the banks of the Vistula River just a few miles from the historic city of Kraków, in 1949. By contrast to its older neighbor, Nowa Huta was intended to model a new kind of socialist modernity and to be peopled with "new men," themselves both the builders and the beneficiaries of this project of socialist construction. Nowa Huta was the largest and politically most significant of the socialist cities built in East Central Europe after World War II; home to the massive Lenin Steelworks, it epitomized the Stalinist program of forced industrialization that opened the cities to rural migrants and sought fundamentally to transform the structures of Polish society.Focusing on Nowa Huta's construction and steel workers, youth brigade volunteers, housewives, activists, and architects, Katherine Lebow explores their various encounters with the ideology and practice of Stalinist mobilization by seeking out their voices in memoirs, oral history interviews, and archival records, juxtaposing these against both the official and unofficial transcripts of Stalinism. Far from the gray and regimented landscape we imagine Stalinism to have been, the fledgling city was a colorful and anarchic place where the formerly disenfranchised (peasants, youth, women) hastened to assert their leading role in "building socialism"—but rarely in ways that authorities had anticipated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCommunism and culturexHistoryxPolandxKraków. 0aCommunism and culturezPolandzKrakówxHistory. 0aCommunism and culturezPolandzKrakówxHistory. 0aWork-life balancexHistoryx20th centuryxPolandxKraków. 0aWork-life balancezPolandzKrakówxHistoryy20th century. 0aWork-life balancezPolandzKrakówxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 4aUrban Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146886540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801468865423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801468865/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066587